In Linux, Load Average represents the average number of processes in a runnable or uninterruptible (waiting for I/O) state over 1, 5, and 15-minute intervals. Analyzing it requires distinguishing between a CPU bottleneck and an I/O bottleneck. 

1. Assess the Scale
Compare the load average to the number of CPU cores using nproc or lscpu. 

Load < Cores: The system is underutilized.
Load > Cores: Processes are queuing, and the system may be overloaded. 

2. Identify the Bottleneck Type
Use vmstat 1 to categorize the load based on CPU time distribution: 

High %us (User): The load is CPU-bound by application code (e.g., heavy computations or inefficient loops).
High %sy (System): Excessive kernel-level activity, often due to high context switching or interrupt handling.
High %wa (I/O Wait): The load is I/O-bound. The CPU is idle but waiting for disk or network operations to complete. 

3. Drill Down into Processes
Once the bottleneck type is known, use specialized tools to find the culprit: 
For CPU-bound issues: Use top or htop and sort by %CPU (press P in top or F6 in htop).
For I/O-bound issues: Use iotop to see real-time disk read/write per process, or iostat -x 1 to identify specific saturated disk partitions.
For Uninterruptible Sleep: Search for processes in the D state using ps -eo pid,state,cmd | grep " D". These processes contribute to load but don't show high CPU usage. 

4. Forensic (Historical) Analysis
If the spike has already passed, use SAR (System Activity Reporter) to review historical data: 
sar -q: Historical load averages.
sar -u: Historical CPU utilization.
sar -d: Historical disk I/O activity. 

These technical guides offer troubleshooting steps for analyzing high load averages on Linux servers by identifying CPU or I/O bottlenecks.

In Linux, a bottleneck occurs when one specific resource (CPU, Memory, Disk, or Network) reaches its limit, causing other processes to queue and slowing down the entire system. 
You can identify these visually using common command-line tools:

1. CPU Bottleneck (The "Busy" System) 

The system is doing too much work and cannot keep up with the task list. 
Top/Htop: You will see %us (User) or %sy (System) consistently above 80-90%. In htop, the CPU bars will be nearly "full" and colored.
vmstat: The r (runnable) column will consistently exceed the number of CPU cores.
Symptom: Commands feel laggy, and the Load Average is much higher than the number of CPUs. 

2. Disk I/O Bottleneck (The "Waiting" System) 

The CPU is capable of working but is "stuck" waiting for the slow hard drive to read or write data. 
Top/vmstat: Look for high %wa (I/O Wait). Anything consistently over 15-20% indicates the disk is holding up the CPU.
iostat -xz 1: Look for %util close to 100%. Also, watch the await column; if it exceeds 20ms, your disk is struggling to keep up with requests.
Symptom: The system feels completely frozen for several seconds at a time while the disk light stays solid. 

3. Memory Bottleneck (The "Swapping" System) 

The system has run out of RAM and is using the hard drive as emergency memory (Swap), which is thousands of times slower. 
free -h: Look at the available column (not just free). If it is near zero, you are in danger.
vmstat: Watch the si (swap-in) and so (swap-out) columns. If these are non-zero and active, the system is "thrashing".
Symptom: High Disk I/O wait and a sudden, massive drop in application performance. 

4. Network Bottleneck (The "Clogged" Pipe)

Data is moving slower than the application requires, or packets are being dropped.
sar -n DEV 1: Shows throughput per interface. Compare rxkB/s and txkB/s against your interface's theoretical limit (e.g., 1Gbps).
ss -s: Look for high numbers in the Send-Q or Recv-Q columns, which means data is sitting in a buffer waiting to be processed.
Symptom: Connection timeouts and slow file transfers despite low CPU/Disk usage. 

Summary Checklist for Next Steps

Your bottleneck is I/O-induced CPU pressure. To find the specific culprit, run these commands:

Find the process reading from disk:
iotop -o (This will show you exactly which process is generating those 500k+ blocks of reads).

Check which disk is saturated:
iostat -xz 1 (Look for the disk with 100% %util).

Check for "Uninterruptible Sleep" processes:
ps aux | awk '$8 ~ /D/' (Processes in the 'D' state are those stuck waiting for disk, contributing to that high r count).

To analyze which processes are "maxing out" your system resources, you need to look at three specific dimensions: CPU, Memory, and I/O.

On a 46-core RAC system, a single process might only show 2% total CPU usage but could still be a bottleneck if it's single-threaded or stuck in I/O wait.

1. Identify CPU-Maxed Processes
If your CPU load is high, use top or htop to find the "Top Talkers."
Command: top -b -n 1 -o %CPU | head -n 20
What to look for:
%CPU: If this is >100% on a multi-core system, the process is multi-threaded.
SHR (Shared Memory): For Oracle, this should be high (SGA). If it's low, the process might not be attached to the SGA correctly.
Command: Press 1 while in top to see the load distribution across all 46 cores.

2. Identify Memory-Maxed Processes
Since you have 80GB of RAM, you want to ensure no process is causing "paging" or "swapping."
Command: ps -eo pid,ppid,cmd,%mem,rss --sort=-rss | head -n 15
Columns to watch:
RSS (Resident Set Size): The actual physical memory the process is using (in KB).
%MEM: The percentage of total RAM used by that process.
Oracle Tip: Many Oracle processes will show high memory because they all map to the same Shared Memory (SGA). Look for processes where RSS is significantly higher than others.

3. Identify I/O-Maxed Processes (The "Silent" Bottleneck)
In your earlier vmstat output, you had high wa (I/O Wait). A process can max out the system without using much CPU if it's hitting the disk too hard.
Command: iotop -oPa
-o: Show only processes actually doing I/O.
-P: Show processes instead of threads.
-a: Show accumulated I/O since the command started (great for finding "bursty" processes).
What to look for: The DISK READ and DISK WRITE columns. On a RAC system, look for dbw0 (Database Writer) or ora_lms (Global Cache Service) processes.

4. Advanced: Analysis by "Thread State"
Sometimes a process isn't using CPU but is still the bottleneck because it's Blocked.
Find "Uninterruptible Sleep" (D State) processes:

ps -eo state,pid,cmd | grep "^D"

Processes in D state are usually waiting for Disk I/O or Network Filesystems (NFS). In RAC, if an ASM disk is slow, you will see many Oracle processes in this state.

